Analyzing Gaming Company Sales and Impact from 1978 to 2016

By Jessica Nah and Sam Chen

Introduction¶

When trying to think of a topic that was both interesting and worthwhile to explore through the means of the data science pipeline, we searched through a fragment of the wealth of information and data that is available on the Internet for the general public to access. As avid gamers, both of us can relate to how significant video games were during our childhoods, and it continues to be a part of our everyday routines today (or more accurately, when our school schedules can afford it). Over time, the video game industry itself has only grown in waves; although neither of us have laid our hands on an Atari 2600 console, the image of such an old-school console is a stark contrast to the modern, high-graphics technology that is used today, and it's a testament to the progress made by both technology and the industry. According to SuperData, a leading provider of market intelligence covering the market for gaming across various platforms, the gaming industry grew 12% from \$120.1 billion in 2019 to \\$139.9 billion in 2020, in large part due to the pandemic. Given a dataset of many video game titles with their sales numbers, ratings, and identifying information, we thought it would be interesting to try to analyze how gaming companies have economically grown over time in sales since the early formation of the video game industry. We started off asking the big question, how has the video game industry grown over time and what does it look like now? As we go through the tutorial, you'll see how our exploratory data analysis helps inform which questions are appropriate to ask given the data, and how our original question gets whittled down and refined into something more concrete and specific.

Data Collection/Curation¶

In order to begin our exploration of this question regarding change/growth in the video game industry, we selected datasets that have already been curated online. A dataset curated by Abdulshaheed Alqunber contained the data we were looking for regarding individual video game titles with their sales numbers, ratings, and identifying information.

Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/ashaheedq/video-games-sales-2019
The dataset curated by Abdulshaheed Alqunber was found on kaggle.com and can be downloaded as a .csv file (vgsales-12-4-2019.csv). The dataset contains entries with the name of the video game, the platform on which the game runs, year the video game was released, ESRB maturity rating, publisher and developer of the game, genre of the game, and the number of sales across various regions like North America, Europe, and Japan as well as total global sales. It also imported the critic score and user score for the game when those values were available (generated from reviews on Metacritic.com).

It was interesting to note that, after taking a quick look at the data from both datasets, one piece of data that we are extremely interested in is the number of sales for a particular game. However, there are columns that seem to be exclusive to one another. The Global_Sales, NA_Sales, PAL_Sales, JP_Sales, and Other_Sales would only have number if Total_Shipped was NaN. The inverse was true as well; if Total_Shipped had a numerical value, then the Global_Sales, NA_Sales, PAL_Sales, JP_Sales, and Other_Sales would be missing. After observing this, we figured that these columns are exclusive to one another, and that they actually give the same information we're looking for but in different columns. It is possible that the data itself on vgchartz was formatted in a way that had "Global_Sales" or "Total_Shipped," one or the other but never both. Thus, this observation will help us to deal with the missing values in a simpler way later on.

Data Management and Representation¶

After getting the data, the next part of the data science pipeline is data management and representation. While the data is conveniently located all within one dataframe, such that we do not have to join or merge two separate Pandas dataframes together, we certainly need to "refine" the dataset. Data management and representation in our case primarily means keeping the necessary data columns that we would be using and dropping the unnecessary columns; we also would want to manage missing data properly and drop any entries that are not meaningful. In this case, regarding missing data, we must act upon our initial observation, and change the sales values so that it is all correctly contained within one column (Global_Sales column should be transferred to Total_Shipped column if Total_Shipped is missing). We are also looking to remove entries that are included in the dataset but have little information contained for the entry (sales, publisher, developer, year, etc).

In [642]:
# We know immediately that there are certain columns that can and should be dropped. VGChartz_Score seems to be
# both extremely subjective as well as often missing for most video games. The basename is pretty similar
# to the actual name of the game, and we would only need the regular video game title for identification purposes.
# The rank is nice to show which titles have been the highest selling throughout history, but we also prefer not
# to use this for the analysis (we find it more practical to analyze success from the number of sales for a 
# video game title rather than analyzing success from its historical rank in best-selling games). 

# Finally, last_update, url, status, Vgchartzscore, and img_url seem cool, but not particularly useful for any analysis.
games = games.drop(['Rank', 'basename', 'VGChartz_Score', \
                    'Last_Update', 'url', 'status', 'Vgchartzscore', 'img_url'], axis=1)

# For each row, we inspect its 'Total_Shipped' column to see if data is missing (which most likely means the data
# we're looking for is located in the 'Global_Sales' column). To be sure, we cross-referenced multiple rows with
# the sales data from the website itself, Google, and other datasets to make sure that Global_Sales was the 
# equivalent and correct number to Total_Shipped, and those numbers should've just been in the same column. 
# Global_Sales also happened to be the exact sum of the values for NA_Sales, PAL_Sales, JP_Sales, and Other_Sales.
for index, row in games.iterrows():
    if np.isnan(row['Total_Shipped']):
        games.at[index, 'Total_Shipped'] = row['Global_Sales']

By this point, the Total_Shipped columns if they were missing before should now be filled with correct numerical values taken from the Global_Sales column. If there are any np.NaN values left, it means that no sales data at all was available in the dataset from either column. Regardless, we should be able to drop Global_Sales (and with so many values missing, NA_Sales, PAL_Sales, JP_Sales, and Other_Sales can be dropped because a regional analysis would require a dataset with less missing information for those columns).

Sure enough, we can see that a significant number of entries have missing values pertaining to number of copies shipped, ESRB_Rating, Critic_Score, and User_Score. Regarding rating, critic score, and user score, we may have some need for those column values should they exist, but it would be impossible to know what those values should be if they're missing (and we cannot impute the values for the missing data from other column values). However, if Total_Shipped is missing, this would greatly affect what we seek to analyze. It makes the most sense to ignore those columns and limit our population to the video games where the data for sales is available. Therefore, we create a new dataframe that has this specific population: Video games where the sales are available in the Total_Shipped column. The original 'games' still can be used to keep track of overall video game titles without sales, but if we're looking for video games with sales numbers available, we should use the resulting 'df2' created below.

We've now inspected the missing values in the new dataframe, and we're okay with the missing data that's left for rating, critic scores, and user scores. We surely have to take into consideration these missing values if we want to use those columns for analysis, but for now, we're content knowing the name, genre, year, platform, publisher, and developer of a specific game. Next, we want to determine the timeline of our data, so we group the dataframe by year and chart the number of games published in each year to get a general understanding of the data.

After the year 2016, there begins to be a sharp, irregular decrease in published games. This irregularity seems unrealistic, so we decided to limit our data to the years 1980 to 2016 in order to work with a more reliable dataset. After also looking at the data, we realized that the data beyond 2016 is inaccurate in the sense that it hasn't been updated enough; those video game releases have occurred relatively recently, and We also see that 1970 has a surprising amount of video games, but after some research on a communal forum's discussion of the dataset (linked here: https://github.com/baynebrannen/vgchartz-crawler), VGChartz has an extremely faulty tendency to label years where they are unsure of the video game as 1970. 1970 is an impossible placeholder value given the history of video games. Atari's Pong video game arcade console is considered one of the first video game consoles to exist for consumer entertainment, and it was only released in 1972. If you inspect 1970 video games in the dataset (as shown below), a quick Google search will tell you that those games were actually released much more recently than 1970. We decided that 1978 would be a good initial starting cutoff point.

As for the ending cutoff point, although the video game dataset does accurately include games released until 2020, it wouldn't be ideal to keep our analysis going until 2020. VGChartz is not a reliable site for updating sales immediately; thus, recent games from the past few years have much, much lower sales recorded in the dataset than in reality. For example, God of War from 2018 has 6.15 million sales according to the dataset. However, the title is one of the best-selling games ever on the PS4; it sold over 10 million units in just over a year, and was recently estimated to have surpassed 20 million copies sold.

In order to circumvent our charts from being extremely inaccurate, we chose to arbitrarily demonstrate the video game industry's growth and sales until 2016, which was a reasonable gap from 2021 for VGChartz to have accurate sales information. We did cross-reference video game sales from 2016 to make sure it was more or less accurate for historical sales numbers and not a vast underestimate. Otherwise, we probably would have seen a shocking drop of sales beyond 2016 (and we surely did), to the point of suggesting that the video game industry is about to die, and that is also clearly a false conclusion.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

How has the video game industry grown over time and what does it look like now? Over the past forty years, the gaming industry has grown through new companies, new games, new consoles, and new players. In order to answer our big question, we need to determine a way to measure the growth of the video game industry.

As you can see, there are many categorical and numerical data columns available for us to use in our analysis. Part of the data science process is really understanding which of these columns are useful for the questions we want to ask; furthermore, when we "poke around" the dataset to see what it contains, we can inform and "revise" the questions we want to ask. In other words, which questions are even appropriate to ask with the data we're given? For example, how useful is it to perform an analysis of user score or critic score? It seemed like there were a lot of missing data values regarding the Metacritic ratings, so something that seemed possibly useful at the start might not actually be practical to analyze.

As seen in our bar chart above, the number of published games peaked around 2008 - 2009, and seems to be decreasing since. However, we already know that gaming is not on the decline. With the changing format of games, it may be that published games have only decreased because the playability and lifetime of games have increased. Therefore, simply looking at the number of published games is not a good metric for measuring the growth of the industry.

However, the number of publishers and their associated games were far too many to be usefully analyzed and visualized. So we turned our attention to the game companies behind the gaming platforms.

Game consoles are an important source of revenue for game companies such as Microsoft, Sony, and Nintendo. A game must be played through some sort of platform after all, and in more recent years, subscriptions and the ability to download purchased games instead of inserting a physical copy have made the profitability of game consoles even more apparent. As such, we decided to create a new column in our dataframe to list the console developer of the game's platform.

To help us visualize the data, we created graphs for each notable console developer, with the total historical number of sales made through games published on that console in a given year, tracking the sales through the years 1978 to 2016.

At this point, we would like to make clear that in our data, the number of sales for each game is not how many games were sold that year, but the overall game sales since the game was published in that year. However, the sales still speak to the game’s popularity and success at the time of publishing. It is more likely for a game to have a high amount of sales in the year it was published, with a less significant number of sales the following years. Therefore, we will view the sales listed with each game as representative of the number of sales made the year it was published with this disclaimer in mind.

In [667]:
# for each console developer, create a graph of total game sales per year
for label, group in df2.groupby(['Console Developer']):
    
    # create new dataframe to help plot sales
    consoleDF = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Total Sales', 'Year'])
    
    # add row of each year's total sales into dataframe
    for k, g in group.groupby(['Year']):
        totalSales = g['Total_Shipped'].sum()
        row = {'Total Sales': totalSales, 'Year': k}
        consoleDF = consoleDF.append(row, ignore_index = True)

# return dictionary of year and dataframe's corresponding yearly average sale per game
def salesavg(df, early):
    savg = dict()
    
    for yr, g in df.groupby(['Year']):
        
        # determine time period to include into dictionary
        if early:
            if yr > 1977 and yr < 1994:
                savg[yr] = g['Total_Shipped'].sum()/len(g)
        else:
            if yr > 1993 and yr < 2017:
                savg[yr] = g['Total_Shipped'].sum()/len(g)
    return savg

At this stage, we can begin to fit a polynomial regression model to see the video games sales of different console companies over time (ex: sales for video games for Nintendo released in 1998 year by year until video games released in 2016). It should be fairly clear from the graphs of sales above that there isn't a nice linear model that would fit the data. But, if our regression fit should be polynomial, how do we determine which degree is appropriate? We could easily underfit the data by using a linear regression (degree = 1), but using a 10th degree-order polynomial would probably be an overfit. The last thing we want to do is to create a model that perfectly fits our data, but would probably be less accurate for a future test set. Given the lack of availability of long-term data (we don't have many years), we decided to use the entire data available as the training set and the test set. This means that we're making a best fit for all of our data, but then comparing our data to itself to determine the accuracy of our model. Still, our first order of business is to determine the correct polynomial fit for each console developer company.

In [677]:
def polydeg(df, name):
    # We're keeping track of the degree, linear_score, and RMSE (root mean squred error) for each degree as we
    # upwardly increase to see how the fit looks
    linear_sample_score = []
    poly_degree = []
    rmse = []
    # For each degree, 1 to 6 (7 is excluded in Python range function)
    for degree in range(1, 7):
        # We create a polynomial regression with PolynomialFeatures module in sklearn
        poly_reg = PolynomialFeatures(degree)
         # I pass in the year column as the "x-values" of the data we're trying to fit
        # poly_reg.fit creates different feature coefficients with the appropriate order so we 
        # need to transform our array accordingly
        X_poly = poly_reg.fit_transform(np.array(df['Year']).reshape(-1, 1))
        # Create a new LinearRegression object from sklearn's Linear Regression module
        lin_reg = LinearRegression()
        # Reshaping the Total Sales column as a new array so that we can fit on it as the "y-values"
        y_reshape = np.array(df['Total Sales']).reshape(-1, 1);
        # Find the linear regression fit with our X_poly variable (x-values reshaped into two-dimensional array)
        # as well as our y-reshaped values
        lin_reg.fit(X_poly, y_reshape)
        y_pred = lin_reg.predict(X_poly)
        test_pred = np.array(y_pred)
        # RMSE is the Root Mean Square Error that helps us measure how spread out our residuals are.
        # It's the square of the difference between our y-predicted value and our y-actual value, summed together 
        # and divided by the number of values, and then rooted.
        RMSE=np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(test_pred-y_reshape)))
        # Append our r^2 score to a list for later use
        linear_sample_score.append(r2_score(np.array(df['Total Sales']), y_pred))
        # Append to RMSE list for later use
        rmse.append(RMSE)
        # Append to polynomial degree array for later use
        poly_degree.append(degree)
        # The plot below shows what the predicted values vs. actual values look like with our 
        # polynomial regression fits for polynomials of different degrees
        # Any points that fall on the red line or close to it mean that the predicted and actual values were
        # extremely close to each other for that year's data point
        plt.figure()
        plt.title("Predicted vs. actual for polynomial of degree {} : {}".format(degree, name),fontsize=15)
        plt.xlabel("Actual values")
        plt.ylabel("Predicted values")
        plt.scatter(y_reshape,test_pred)
        plt.plot(y_reshape,y_reshape,'r',lw=2)
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.grid(True)
    # Plot the RMSE(y-variable) vs. polynomial degree(x-variable) with the arrays we stored above
    plt.plot(poly_degree,rmse,lw=3,c='red')
    plt.title("Model complexity (highest polynomial degree) vs. test score\n",fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel ("\nDegree of polynomial",fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel ("Root-mean-square error on test set",fontsize=15)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.grid(True)
    # Plot the R^2 score(y-variable) vs. polynomial degree(x-variable) with the arrays we stored above
    plt.plot(poly_degree,linear_sample_score,lw=3,c='red')
    plt.xlabel ("\nModel Complexity: Degree of polynomial",fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel ("R^2 score on test set",fontsize=15)

Nintendo¶

In [678]:
polydeg(salesNin, "Nintendo")

We can think of first few graphs (labeled Predicted vs. actual for polynomial of degree {n}) as an initial look as to the difference between predicted and actual values for polynomial regression fits with different degrees. However, it doesn't concretely tell us which polynomial degree order is the appropriate one to use. The graphs below will allow us to see which polynomial degree effectively minimizes the RMSE (similar to a gradient descent function). A smaller RMSE means that the residuals are smaller and thus, the polynomial is a better fit. Of course, then, a higher polynomial fit should be result in a smaller RMSE (so it'll keep decreasing as we increase the order). By graphing the change in RMSE below for each degree, we can see which degree significantly drops the RMSE, and then from that point on, future degrees don't have a significant drop. This will allow us to select a polynomial degree that doesn't overfit the data, because we can stop at the degree that effectively minimizes the RMSE to the point where higher degrees don't do minimize the RMSE by that much more.

In this case, we can see for Nintendo, the best degree of polynomial for regression fit is suggested to be 3 (a cubic function). After 3, the RMSE does not drop by that much more, so anything greater than 3 could probably be considered an overfit.

The R^2 score, or the coefficient of determination, is another way in which we can statistically measure how close our data is to the regression line. To be more accurate, it is the proportion of the variance for our sales that's explained by the year in our regression model polynomially. We can see that our R^2 score below might not be that great (60-ish% for Nintendo), but what the graph also shows is that the R^2 score does not significantly increase after the 3rd degree either. So again, anything past the 3rd degree is not effective or necessary, and would probably be considered an overfit.

Final Polynomial Regression Fit Models¶

Now that we have the ideal degree of order for polynomial regression line for each console developer company, we can plot the actual regression fit and see how it looks, while also predicting values to, say, 2020. It'll be interesting to see what our models suggest. Do our models suggest that Nintendo is on the uptrend? Is PC gaming a viable central platform for gaming in the years to come?

def regfit(df, deg, name):
    # First create a scatterplot of the actual values
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.scatter(df["Year"], df["Total Sales"])
    # Now we use PolynomialFeatures to again find a regression line, 
    # but this time we know the degree of the polynomial regression should be for example, 3 for Nintendo
    poly_reg = PolynomialFeatures(degree=deg)
    X_poly = poly_reg.fit_transform(np.array(df['Year']).reshape(-1, 1))
    lin_reg = LinearRegression()
    lin_reg.fit(X_poly, np.array(df['Total Sales']).reshape(-1, 1))
    y_pred = lin_reg.predict(X_poly)
    plt.plot(df['Year'], y_pred, c='red')
    plt.title('Polynomial Regression Fit for' + name)
    
    print(name + ':')
    print('2016 Predicted Value: ' + str(lin_reg.predict(poly_reg.fit_transform([[2016]]))))
    print('2017 Predicted Value: ' + str(lin_reg.predict(poly_reg.fit_transform([[2017]]))))
    print('2018 Predicted Value: ' + str(lin_reg.predict(poly_reg.fit_transform([[2018]]))))
    print('2019 Predicted Value: ' + str(lin_reg.predict(poly_reg.fit_transform([[2019]]))))
    print('2020 Predicted Value: ' + str(lin_reg.predict(poly_reg.fit_transform([[2020]]))))

Final Observations and Reflections¶

Our polynomial regression fits suggest that the average sales per released console game for Nintendo and Microsoft will continue to go down after 2016. It seems likely that Sony will increase their average sales, though the climb will be slow. On the other hand, the sales for PC games had a smaller degree of polynomial fit the data, and are expected to continue an exponential rise. Based on our data analysis from 1978 - 2016, it seems that Sony and PC games will take the lead in the following years. But again, the reliability of our inferences is dependent on the reliability of the data itself; if the sales of games for recent years past 2010 have still not been recorded properly, and are not as high as they actually are, this would explain why companies like Nintendo and Microsoft look like they're on an extreme downtrend. It's also possible, again, that a lack of console releases contributed to an accurate amount of lower sales in recent years, or that game developers are more focused on developing less games, but those games are more successful and playable for longer time periods.

However, more reliable data would need to be acquired about the past four years to see how well our regression fits predicted the average sales of these game console developers. With the releases of the Nintendo Switch, PS5, and Xbox Series X and S in the past four years, it is possible that the trendlines of average sales for these game console companies will alter with the addition of a more recent dataset - for better or for worse. Looking back at our efforts to find patterns in our data, our results were shocking regarding predictions for video game sales for future years, but finding shocking or contradictory results to what we believe is okay! In the hopes of pursuing more accurate results or confirming the trends that were found in our project, we would need to perform further testing and analysis (and probably with self-scraped data from a website that has even more information about a game's sales from month to month, and updates sales more immediately) is preferable; this is something to surely explore down the road. Until then, keep on data scraping, exploring patterns in your data, and testing hypotheses, all while gaming in between!
